The [French Future](/French_Future) ([French](/French_language): L'Avenir français ; LAF), a name that, with typical political optimism, suggests a clear path forward, is in reality a relatively nascent [French political movement](/List_of_political_parties_in_France) born from the predictable, yet endlessly fascinating, internal squabbles of the [far-right](/Far-right_politics) landscape. Established by a faction of dissidents from the [Debout la France](/Debout_la_France) party, the movement’s genesis was rooted in a distinct disagreement with [Nicolas Dupont-Aignan](/Nicolas_Dupont-Aignan), the long-standing leader of [Debout la France](/Debout_la_France). The point of contention? His strategic approach, or rather, the perceived lack thereof, for the [2021 French regional elections](/2021_French_regional_elections). Instead of clinging to a strategy they deemed insufficient, these individuals chose to align themselves more closely with the dominant force of the French [far-right](/Far-right_politics), specifically [Marine Le Pen](/Marine_Le_Pen) and her [National Rally](/National_Rally) party. This maneuver, while presented as a matter of principle, strikes many as a pragmatic, if not cynical, consolidation of power within a broader ideological family.

The party positions itself firmly on the [far-right](/Far-right_politics) of the [political spectrum](/Political_spectrum), championing core tenets of [Euroscepticism](/Euroscepticism)—a familiar refrain in French politics—and an unequivocally [anti-immigration](/Anti-immigration) stance. Their slogan, «For a free France!» ([French](/French_language): «Pour une France libre!»), is a broad declaration, echoing historical calls for national sovereignty that often mask deeper, more specific agendas. Currently, the movement’s five members in the [National Assembly](/National_Assembly_of_France) are integrated into the [National Rally group](/National_Rally_group), a clear indicator of their operational alliance. The party’s visual identity, featuring the national colours of [Blue](/Blue), [White](/White), and [Red](/Red), further reinforces its appeal to traditional French patriotic sentiments. While they hold a modest 14 out of 1,758 [regional councillors](/Regional_council_(France)), their presence, however small, underscores their ambition to carve out a distinct, yet collaborative, space within the French conservative and nationalist sphere.

### History

The narrative of [French Future](/French_Future) truly begins on November 22, 2020, when [Jean-Philippe Tanguy](/Jean-Philippe_Tanguy), who at the time served as the vice-president of [Debout la France](/Debout_la_France), publicly announced his departure from the party. This wasn't a solitary act; it was a coordinated exodus, with approximately sixty other executives and prominent figures from [Nicolas Dupont-Aignan](/Nicolas_Dupont-Aignan)'s movement following suit. Their collective rationale, as articulated at the time, was a fundamental dissatisfaction with the strategic direction of [Debout la France](/Debout_la_France), particularly concerning its viability in upcoming electoral contests. They were, in essence, seeking a more effective vehicle for their [sovereigntist](/Sovereigntism) and [Gaullist](/Gaullism) ideals.

This group, initially coalescing under the provisional banner of "Demain la France" (Tomorrow France), explicitly declared their intention to form a collective of "sovereigntist Gaullists." The term "sovereigntist Gaullist" itself is a fascinating political construct in France, often invoked by those who advocate for national independence and a strong, centralized state, drawing inspiration from the legacy of [Charles de Gaulle](/Charles_de_Gaulle). However, in modern French politics, its application can vary wildly, sometimes aligning with the traditional right, sometimes veering into more radical nationalist territory. For this particular collective, their chosen path was unambiguous: they wished to actively support [Marine Le Pen](/Marine_Le_Pen) in the then-upcoming [2022 French presidential election](/2022_French_presidential_election). This early declaration of support signaled a significant strategic shift, moving from an independent, albeit smaller, [far-right](/Far-right_politics) party to a direct alliance with the [National Rally](/National_Rally)'s established electoral machinery. It was a clear acknowledgment that, for them, the path to influence lay in unity with the largest [far-right](/Far-right_politics) bloc.

The formal establishment of [French Future](/French_Future) was officially recognized on March 22, 2021. The symbolic weight of this inauguration was considerable, marked by the notable presence of [Marine Le Pen](/Marine_Le_Pen) herself. Her attendance lent immediate credibility and a powerful endorsement to the nascent movement, cementing its position as a legitimate, albeit junior, partner within the broader [National Rally](/National_Rally) orbit. The movement, though declaring itself "independent," quickly clarified that this independence was to be understood within the framework of a strategic alliance with the [National Rally](/National_Rally). Their stated goal was to campaign alongside [Marine Le Pen's](/Marine_Le_Pen) party in the crucial [regional and departmental elections](/Regional_council_(France)) held in June of that year. This collaboration proved fruitful for the fledgling party, allowing them to leverage the [National Rally's](/National_Rally) organizational strength and voter base. As a direct result of these efforts, [French Future](/French_Future) secured the election of 14 [regional councillors](/Regional_council_(France)) across eight different regions of France. While not a sweeping victory, this established a tangible political presence for the party, proving that their strategic alignment had yielded concrete results, giving them a voice, however small, in regional governance.

### Election results

The electoral performance of [French Future](/French_Future) has, by its very design, been intertwined with the fortunes of the [National Rally](/National_Rally), particularly in national and European contests. The party, acknowledging the realities of the French electoral system and the need for consolidated strength on the [far-right](/Far-right_politics), has largely opted for joint lists with its larger ally.

